post_text: Just after the start of the school day, North Gibson was informed of a potential threat in the community that was being investigated by law enforcement. The potential threat was not specific to North Gibson, however, out of extra precaution, we decided to keep our students inside the building today. Law enforcement has investigated the threat and determined there to be no danger to our students or staff at this time. While we will continue to keep our students indoors today, we anticipate a full return to normal school day activities for tomorrow. We will have normal after school activities this afternoon.

post_text:
NGSC has been actively planning for possible learning scenarios in the event we experience increased Covid-19 cases within our schools. In order to help parents prepare, we are releasing the two possible alternative learning models that we may need to implement during the 2020-2021 school year.

Please read the Hybrid Attendance Model carefully to know when your child would attend school IF we need to implement the Hybrid Attendance Model. If this model needed to be implemented, we will do our best to give some advanced notice.

Again, this is simply being released to allow parents to be prepared. While our goal is to remain in our current in-person learning model, we will collaborate with our local health department in the event we begin to see confirmed cases within our schools to determine if we need to implement one of these models. #MaskUp #StayatZero

Too good to not share. Pictured is Justin Hyneman, transportation technician/bus driver, doing his best Corona Buster impression as he prepares to sanitize a school bus.

On a serious note, our transportation staff sanitizes our buses after each morning and evening route. This is very important to mitigate the spread of Covid-19. Additionally, our custodial staff is sanitizing all learning spaces each day using our Chlorox 360 machines. This, along with our typical daily cleaning of hard surfaces is also critical to mitigate Covid-19. We are very appreciative of our excellent transportation and facilities staff for all the extra care they are putting into sanitizing each day.

We have had a great start to our school year. Students and staff are doing an excellent job following guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing as much a possible. We again want to remind our parents and students of the CDC requirements for determining when a student can return to school after experiencing symptoms of Covid-19, having a positive test, and/or being identified as a close contact of someone who tested positive.

For us to remain open and keep our staff and students as healthy as possible, it is critical that students follow these guidelines. We will strictly enforce these guidelines. Let's all work together to keep our cases at ZERO for as long as possible.

For the immediate time being, individual tickets will be sold to game night events in compliance with the number of patrons allowed to attend. I apologize for any inconvenience this may cause. We are working diligently to abide by all guidance to maintain the safest standards of compliance for our athletes, coaches and patrons. More information will be forthcoming as information allows. Many thanks and GO TIGERS! - Jason

NGSC custodial staff was busy installing barriers in classroom computer labs this weekend. Just another step we are taking to provide protection for students and staff as computer lab configurations cannot change due to locations for plugging into power and our network drops. This doesnâ€™t eliminate the important need for wearing face coverings, but it does provide a barrier between students sitting next to each other in closer proximity than they do in a traditional classroom.

A special thank you to Anchor Industries for fulfilling our order for barriers in a very short time frame.

We want to give a huge THANK YOU to the North Gibson Education Foundation. Their generous donation of school supplies saved our families over $5,000 combined this year. We are very fortunate to have a foundation to provide our students, parents, and teachers this kind of support!

July 31 at 2:01 PM Â·

We are happy to share that the Foundation is donating over $5,000 in school supplies to NGSC students. We were fortunate to receive funds from the Gibson County Community Foundation-Rapid Response Grant which helped fund the majority of the supplies. This year every student in NGSC will benefit from the donation of supplies.

PCPS-Glue Sticks and Expo Markers
PCIS-Folders and Expo Markers
PCMS-Composition Notebook, pens and mechanical pencils. Calculators for Math classes grades 6-8.
PCHS-Loose leaf paper, pens, mechanical pencils.

It is because of foundation members and community support that we are able to do special projects like this. If you would like to become a member of the foundation for $25, per school year, please reach out to us.

Have a great school year! Go Tigers!

North Gibson School Corporation will now be offering a Virtual Learning Academy for any student who wishes to pursue an alternative learning environment instead of returning to school in person. This decision was made in consideration of feedback from our parents who were seeking an alternative learning environment.

Please review the attached informational sheet explaining all the details of what this Virtual Learning Option will entail. If your student has already applied for the virtual learning option due to health concerns, there is no need to reapply. The final date to be accepted into the Virtual Learning Option will be Friday, July 31 at 3:00 PM. Once an application is complete, contact will be made from the school level to finalize enrollment into the Virtual Learning Option.

In accordance with local health department approval, in-person learning is still scheduled to begin on August 7. We look forward to the start of the school year.

Our Re-entry committee has been working hard to develop the specific details of our Re-Entry plan. We are making great progress.

We are happy to announce that we have full intentions of all students returning to school buildings on Aug. 7 with social distancing practices in place. The specifics of those social distancing practices, including the wearing of masks by students and staff and much more are still in development. We hope to release additional details of our planning in July.

Princeton Community Middle School
June 11 at 2:37 PM Â·

Public Service Announcement:
We have heard from a handful of parents who have told us that they have checked their student's 20-21 schedule in Harmony (our student management system) and it does not seem to be correct.

Student schedules for the upcoming school year are not finished; they are still being completed and balanced. In fact, PCMS staff have currently set parent's and student's ability to see schedules Harmony to "Off" in order to avoid confusion until all schedules are completed. Unfortunately this feature is not working. We have reached out to Harmony in order to find a solution, but at this time have not heard back from them.

Typically, we release completed student schedules in early July, and we are on schedule to do so again this year. We will email parents as well as post a notification on this page when schedules are complete and have been released.

We appreciate your patience and apologize for any confusion.

post_text:
As many of our parents and students will be seeing on their timelines, today, the state released guidelines for the return to school. North Gibson has developed a Re-entry Committee of Administration, Teachers, Staff and Parents who will be working diligently over the next month to develop a specific plan for return to school using these guidelines. Additionally, we will be working collaboratively with our local health officials to provide guidance on our Re-entry plan.

While we are eager to have students returning to school, our focus will be to do this as safely as possible while maintaining a quality educational experience for our students. We look forward to providing information to our parents, students, and community at some point in July.

PCHS Graduation has been rescheduled for July 18, 2020, at 2pm, in Tiger Arena. Mandatory graduation practice for seniors is scheduled for Friday, July 17th, at 12pm.

This school year has ended in a way that none of us would have ever wanted or dreamt of. Having to reschedule an important event like graduation is never easy and we realize it may cause conflicts with already set plans or vacations. We also realize that several seniors will not be able to attend in July due to prior commitments such as Basic Training, early college programs, job opportunities, etc. and for that, we will always be sad and full of regret.

Therefore, PCHS has also scheduled a â€œParade of Seniorsâ€ event on May 23rd at 2pm. Information regarding the route will be posted at a later date. Detailed information has been emailed out to all seniors.

We want to share our appreciation for all the nurse heroes in our community and beyond. Your fight on the front lines during this pandemic is greatly appreciated.

At NGSC, our schools are blessed with outstanding nursing staff who provide excellent care for our students each and every day! We are thankful for each and every one of them! Thank you for taking care of our students!

Fun Fact: PCHS has a CNA program to provide an opportunity for high school students to earn their CNA and explore the field of nursing. If you are a student interested in nursing, this is a great way to start your career!

post_text:
Summer Activities Update:

School are mandated to remain closed to student activities through June 30. Therefore, we will be adjusting the following activities:

High Ability STEM Camp: Cancelled

High School Summer School (Credit Recovery): Online only, no in person class meetings. If you have not signed up for High School Summer School, and are in need for recovering credits, contact PCHS on Monday or Wednesday from 8:00-12:00 or email your guidance counselor.

Elementary and Middle School Summer School will still be occurring as planned during the weeks of July 20-31. If we are not allowed to have in-person classes, we will provide an update to our plans.

Any athletic events, youth camps, etc., during June will either be cancelled or postponed. Look for additional information from those program coaches or sponsors in the near future.

post_text:
Mask Donation Update:

We have had a great response for assistance with mask donations. If you have not made contact with us but are still interested in assisting, please contact Nurse Director, Julie Koberstein at jkoberstein@ngsc.k12.in.us.

To streamline donations, we will be placing donation boxes inside the main entrance at Princeton Community High School. Donations of masks or materials can be placed in the marked boxes on Monday's and Wednesday's from 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM and on Wednesday from 4:00 PM to 6:00 PM.

We greatly appreciate the support we are already receiving.

We also want to reiterate that our request in simply planning ahead to be prepared IF masks are a requirement for school to reopen. We have made no decisions, nor have we been provided the mandate that students and staff will be required to wear masks. Again, we are simply working to be prepared IF this is required.

Additionally, as always, you can follow the progress of the meeting agenda live through our Board Docs site (Does not include video) at https://go.boarddocs.com/in/ngsc/Board.nsf/Public

post_text: As the governor has announced just minutes ago, all schools are now mandated to remain closed for the rest of the 2019-2020 school year. District and school administration will be sorting through the state requirements and will provide an update to the learning plans for students next week. Students should continue completing E-learning/Learning Packets as planned through May 1. It is essential that this work is being completed. Our updated plans to be released next week will address requirements of students beyond May 1. We know there will be many questions, and we will answer those after we have reviewed updated guidance from the Indiana Department of Education. We appreciate your patience as we continue to navigate this newest executive order.

Effective March 16, 2020 through May 1, 2020 - Per the Indiana Dept of Labor, in conjunction with Governor Holcomb's mandated school closing date, they are suspending enforcement of:

1) the requirement for employers to have on-file work permits for minor employees, and
2) the requirement to have permission letters from the school allowing minors to work during restricted hours of 7:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m. on E-Learning days (applicable to 16- and 17-year-old employees only)

This is a tough way to end a season, but we thank our archers, parents, and schools for support of this new sport!!!

PCHS Tigers - Princeton Community High School
March 20 at 2:10 PM Â·

Due to Governor Holcombâ€™s closure of all Indiana schools through May 1st, PCHS will need to postpone our Prom. Unfortunately, due to the constantly fluid nature of the Coronavirus situation, we are not able to safely secure a new date at this time. It is our hope that this is only a postponement and that we will be able to hold the Prom at some point in the future.

As for Graduation, it is still scheduled for May 23rd. We are committed to doing whatever we can to make sure that graduation happens. With that being said, there may be additional federal and/or state mandates that completely change our plans, so we will do our best to monitor the situation and keep you updated on any changes.

Stay safe, stay healthy and stay tuned!

1.) Hazleton Community Center Parking Lot
2.) Patoka United Methodist Church Parking Lot
3.) Mount Olympus Gym Parking Lot
4.) Sandy Acres Trailer Court at the office
5.) Princeton Creek Apartments at the Office Building Parking Lot
6.) Deda Young Park (Ford and Brumfield Area)
7.) Mulberry St. Apartments

We will also continue to have pick-up at Princeton Community Middle School at door 26 from 11:00-1:00.

Please share!

post_text:
Attention elementary students and parents:

Starting this evening, we will have a mystery reader from one of our elementary schools going Live on our page to read a story. Starting at around 5:00 PM, clues about the mystery reader will be posted. At 7:00 PM, the mystery reader will go live on this page to read to students.

Our teachers miss their students and we know that our students miss their teachers. This is a fun way to continue spreading the love of reading and to connect with our students. We hope to do this again on Friday with a new mystery reader. If possible, we will continue doing this each week night.

Join us this evening!

PCPS and PCIS teachers, check your email and respond to Dr. Goggins if you are interested in being a mystery reader, BUT DON'T RESPOND ON THIS POST. We want to keep it a mystery!

post_text: As we reflect on a whirlwind first two days of school closure due to COVID-19, we couldnâ€™t help but notice the bright spots in a difficult situation. Teachers and instructional support staff working diligently to prepare lessons, food service staff pitched in with smiles on their face to establish a FREE meal program for ALL students in NGSC. Our custodial and maintenance staff are working diligently to clean and prepare buildings for eventual return of students. Office staff answering calls and making copies of learning packets. Bus drivers will be pitching in to help get meals to various locations in the community starting on Thursday. Administration is leading and directing through ever changing information from state and federal officials. We are very fortunate and appreciative of everyoneâ€™s willingness to do whatever it takes for our students and community. Together, we are making the best of this difficult situation. That is Tiger Pride! Students and parents, please know that we are here to support you through the E-learning lessons.

Parents/Guardians,

Please see the picture below for list of items that we encourage families to pick up from school. PCMS will be open on Monday from 8am-3pm. This, along with our increased sanitization of school facilities, is essential to help prevent the spread of illness.

post_text:
We would like to recognize our Standing Ovation Award winners from Princeton Community Primary School.

Sara Abbey, 1st Grade Special Education Teacher, was recognized by her coworkers for being an awesome team player. She looks at every student as being her own and is always available to help. She is always willing to give PCPS student support in whatever way they need it. She does everything needed and never complains. She is an all-around outstanding teacher.

Natalie Teeters, Cafeteria Manager at Primary South, was recognized by her coworkers for always going above and beyond for students and staff. She provides great service from the cafeteria for everyone. She even takes the opportunity to coordinate lunches with special days at the school. She always does these things with a smile on her face.

Thank you Mrs. Abbey and Ms. Teeters for your dedication to the PCPS students and staff and your excellent service to North Gibson School Corporation.

North Gibson Archery is headed to State!! Way to go archers! Middle and High School teams qualified for state. Max Williams and Luke Kunkel qualified as individuals in elem. division!
PCMS qualified 6th out of 40 teams.
PCHS qualifies 23 out or 36.
Max and Luke were 2 out of only 11 individuals they took for elem div. (with only 10 archers in our Elem division, we don't have enough to make a team. So they have to qualify individually.)

3800 archers attempted to qualify; they only took 2160. So proud of North Gibson Archery!!!

post_text:
The 2020 US Census is nearing and it is critical that everyone in our district is counted. The census has a direct correlation to school funding as well as critical funding for Gibson County, hospitals, and more. Beginning March 12, the U.S. Census Bureau will invite everyone living in the United State to complete a census questionnaire online, by phone or by mail. Please take the time to complete the questionnaire. Completing the questionnaire will have no negative effects on you or your family. It will only positively affect your community. Spread the Word!

https://2020census.gov/en/how-to-help.html

5th grade students at PCIS are working on Robotics and Automation. They were given the task of building this Chassis robot with a group by watching a video. Then, they will use the base model to design an attachment for collecting blocks and moving them to a secure location. They love Project Lead the Way Launch!

Video to follow!

Adrian - 1st Place in Creative Solutions for Southern Indiana (moves on to state competition)

Savanna - trophy in Critical Thinking
